<DOCNO> XIE19980405.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Wheat Production to Exceed Target: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Minister for Food,
Agriculture and Livestock Abdul Sattar Laleka said Saturday the
wheat production this year is expected to exceed the target of 18
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is expecting a bumper wheat crop owing to better
weather conditions, enhanced agriculture credit and balanced use
of fertilizers, said the minister in an interview with PTV
(Pakistan TV).
</P>
<P>
Laleka said that small farmers, who constitute 81 per cent of
the agricultural community, took advantage of the facilities
provided by the government and cultivated a record area of 20.7
million acres this year.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had
announced an agriculture package for the farmers on April 3,
giving incentives to the small farmers having less than 12.5 acres
of land in a bid to enhance the production of wheat.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has also increased the allocation of
agriculture loans from 12 billion rupees (273 million U.S. dollars
) to 30 billion rupees (682 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Owing to the government's policy to enhance wheat production,
the use of urea fertilizer was increased from 1.6 million tons to
two million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
Laleka said the recent country-wide rains also helped to grow a
better wheat crop and he hoped it would enhance wheat production.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that an action is being chalked out to
produce quality seeds in a bid to boost agriculture production.
The plan will be presented for final approval shortly, said
Laleka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
