<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former UNITA Representative to Portugal Ordered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Portugal has ordered former
Representative of the National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) Issac Wambembe to leave the country, the Angolan
News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Portuguese visa office on March
30 notified Wambembe that his residence visa which expired on
March 31 would not be extended.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure of the resolution on sanctions against
UNITA passed in October 1997 by the United Nations Security
Council, UNITA's representing office in Portugal was renamed as
Angola Democracy Development Center, and Wambembe was the head of
the organ.
</P>
<P>
UNITA spokesman in Portugal said Saturday in Lisbon that
Wambembe is still in the capital and he has brought a suit to
court.
</P>
<P>
The notification signed by State Secretary of Interior Affairs
Armando Vara explained that Wambembe was denied residence visa
because UNITA did not complete its tasks stipulated in the 1994
Lusaka Peace Accord. And in line with the Security Council's
Resolution 1127/97, U.N. member states should restrict activities
of UNITA in their territories.
</P>
<P>
As the U.N. resolution is still in force, sanctions against
UNITA include shut-down of the overseas delegation offices of the
opposition movement and restriction on visits by its leaders and
their families.
</P>
<P>
After the sanction resolution was adopted, UNITA has renamed
many of its offices in the western states as the so-called Angola
Democracy Development Centers to continue their political
activities.
</P>
<P>
The visa office of Portugal disclosed that the decision to
order Wambembe to leave the country was made by "higher-level
leaders". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
