<HEADLINE> Hamas Calls for Revenge Attacks Against Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The militant Palestinian group
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), held a big rally in Gaza
Saturday calling for revenge attacks against Israel over the
death of Hamas bomb maker Muhi Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 pro-Hamas Palestinian students held an anti-Israeli
demonstration at the campus of Gaza's Islamic University and
later marched through central streets in central city.
Protesters, waving the green Hamas flags, chanted anti-Israeli
slogans and burned Israeli flags.
</P>
<P>
They called on the Hamas military wing Izzedin Kassim to
launch attacks against Israeli targets inside and outside Israel
to avenge the death of Sharif, who was killed in a controversial
car bombing in Ramallah last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Despite Israel's strong denial, Hamas has been accusing Israel
of murdering Sharif, whose burned body was found inside a bombed
car. Some reports said he was killed hours before the car bomb
was set off to cover his assassination.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) condemned
the killing of Sharif in a statement issued by the PNA Cabinet
which met Friday night in Ramallah. The statement denounced
Sharif' killing as a "terrible crime," but it did not name who was
responsible for his death. Earlier, the Palestinian Legislative
Council issued a statement, blaming Israel for murdering Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The PNA Cabinet called on Hamas leaders to cooperate with
Palestinian security forces in continuing the investigation into
Sharif's death. It also promised to publish the investigation
results once they are achieved.
</P>
<P>
Following Sharif's death, Palestinian security heads have met
with Hamas political leaders in Gaza in an attempt to prevent
Hamas attacks against Israel. Israeli government has warned that
the PNA would be held responsible for any such attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have been put on high alert
throughout the country to guard against possible terror attacks
by Hamas, which has not launched any attacks in Israel since
last September's bombing of the Ben Yehuda pedestrian mall in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police Inspector-General Yehuda Wilk said the current
security alert would continue throughout the upcoming one-week
Passover holiday beginning on Monday and the Independence Day
celebrations early next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
