<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-French Relations On Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji is
visiting France on April 5-7 to give a boost to bilateral
relations which have seen a steady growth for recent years.
</P>
<P>
The visit, at the invitation of French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, is another high-level exchange of the two sides designed
to build a long term and stable relationship, following Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's visit to Paris in September 1994.
</P>
<P>
Sino-French friendship boasts a long history. In 1964, French
President Charles de Gaulle recognized the People's Republic of
China, making France the first major Western power to establish
formal ties with China. Chairman Mao Zedong and General de Gaulle
agreed to develop and strengthen bilateral relations in view of
safeguarding world peace.
</P>
<P>
It is proved by historical facts that healthy and steady
relations between China and the Western countries not only conform
to the wish and interests of their peoples, but also are conducive
to world peace, stability and development.
</P>
<P>
Sino-French relations experienced zigzags in the early 1990s
and bilateral exchanges in some fields suffered a setback.
</P>
<P>
With renewed efforts of both governments, Sino-French relations
were normalized when President Jiang paid a state visit to
France. The visit again set into motion the engine of friendly
Sino-French cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Since May 1995, when Chirac became president of France, there
has been a new elan for the development of Sino-French
relations. High level exchanges increased. Improved political
relationship promoted bilateral cooperation in economy, trade,
science and technology and culture.
</P>
<P>
The most powerful driving force behind the steady growth of
Sino-French relations is their sharing of a similar or identical
view on the post-Cold War world situation.
</P>
<P>
The two, opposing any attempt to build a mono-polar world,
believe that the world's move toward a multi-polar structure is
accelerating. As a multi-polar world is taking shape, a reinforced
relationship between China and France, as well as between Asia and
Europe, is important in safeguarding world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
That's why the leaders of the two countries attach strategic
importance to developing bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
China and France, both permanent members of the United Nations
Security Council, have major impact on world politics. They are
expected to make important contribution to the world peace through
closer consultation and stable and lasting bilateral relations of
friendly cooperation for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
During the recent Iraqi crisis, China insisted on its solution
through peaceful means while France opposed the use of force
against Iraq. Both contributed to a peaceful settlement of the
crisis and won praise from the international community.
</P>
<P>
Another driving force behind Sino-French relations is the
tremendous potential for mutually beneficial cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
France believes that China's rapid economic and social
development over the past two decades is changing and will decide
the balance of the world.
</P>
<P>
But as the world's fourth largest economic power, France
currently has taken up only two percent of the Chinese market, not
in proportion with its economic might.
</P>
<P>
In the triangular economic relationships among Asia, North
America and Europe, the one between Europe and Asia is not as
strong as that between Europe and North America or between Asia
and North America.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Asia and Europe in the fields of
politics, economy and culture must be strengthened, in which the
reinforced economic and trade ties between China and France will
surely have its place.
</P>
<P>
The economic development in China not only improves the living
standards of the Chinese people but also provides new impetus for
the growth of the world economy as well as more commercial
opportunities for the developed countries. China, an emerging
market with great potentials, shares a complementary economy with
France.
</P>
<P>
Last May, President Jiang Zemin and President Jacques Chirac
signed the Sino-French Joint Declaration in Beijing, expressing
their willingness to join hands in building a multi-polar,
harmonious, more stable and peaceful world. China and France also
inked over 10 other documents to bring bilateral cooperation
into a new phase of steady development.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu's visit to France will surely push further
forward the all-round development of Sino-French relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
