<HEADLINE> UK, Ireland Optimistic on N.Irish Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Both UK Prime Minister Tony Blair
and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, expressed confidence
Friday in the Northern Ireland peace process, saying an agreement
is within sight.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers made the statement after holding talks
on the intensifying Northern Irish peace process in London Friday
and pledged "intense contact" over the weekend with all the
participants of the peace talks in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, meeting on the fringes of an Asia-Europe
summit, said that a deal could be reached with "realistic
negotiation."
</P>
<P>
The deadline for a peace agreement was set for April 9, but
deep divisions still exist between Catholic and Protestant
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the chairman of the peace talks, former U.S. senator
George Mitchell, said Friday evening that a political settlement
is in sight, but he had failed to complete an agenda for a
settlement as he had planned.
</P>
<P>
The agenda was originally planned to be put to the parties
involved in the peace talks Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The document was supposed to pave the way for a final
settlement early next week and to list areas of agreement and
other issues he wants to try to resolve in meetings.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, UK Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam and
Gerry Adams, the leader of the Irish Republican Army's political
wing Sinn Fein, also expressed optimism that a peace deal could be
reached within the deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
