<HEADLINE> Normal Weather for Farming Expected in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A near-normal agricultural season
is now being predicted by many weather watchers, helping to
slightly uplift sentiment in the farming sector and the economy
at large, the Zimbabwe National Chamber of Commerce said in a
newsletter Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Horticulture will be reportedly doing well while tobacco,
cotton and maize should witness increased output.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the good news on the rainfall front, overall
economic prospects still remained gloomy, the Zimbabwe News
Agency quoted the newletter as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy was officially projected to have
registered a growth rate of 3.7 percent in 1997 compared to 7.2
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe figures,
growth in 1997 was underpinned by manufacturing which grew by
18.7 percent as a percentage of GDP, up from 17.9 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is estimated to have grown by 16.5 percent down
from 17.5, mining by 3.9 percent down from 4.3 percent and
tourism by 19.1 up from 18.4 percent in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
