<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Remains Hopeful of Agreement on N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said Saturday that he "remains very much full of hope" that the
parties in the Northern Ireland peace talks will be able to reach
a settlement in time for an April 9 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a television interview, Blair said the peace
process had now reached a critical stage and there was a "one-off
chance" to bring the trouble to an end.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he acknowledged that there are difficulties to be
overcome as deep divisions still exist between Catholic and
Protestant leaders.
</P>
<P>
As the deadline for an agreement approaches, Northern Ireland's
main political parties involved in the peace talks are working
through the weekend in Belfast to try to hammer out a settlement.
</P>
<P>
"We're certainly making progress and I remain very much full of
hope but obviously these things are difficult, they are
painstaking," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
He added that a peaceful and successful future for the province
was in reach "if we have the courage to take it," and "it's
important that we make sure the agreement we can get to is the
best."
</P>
<P>
However, the chairman of the peace talks, former U.S. senator
George Mitchell, failed to complete a draft settlement Friday as
planned.
</P>
<P>
But according to Paul Murphy, a junior minister for Northern
Ireland, the document will be produced over the next few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
