<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ruling Party Said to Be in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The National Youth League of the
ruling ZANU (PF) of Zimbabwe Saturday warned that there is "open
hostility" towards the ruling party and appealed to President
Robert Mugabe to provide guidance on how best to surmount the
numerous problems bedeviling the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the on-going session of the ZANU Youth League
National Assembly, Secretary for Youth Affairs of the Natinal
Youth League Josiah Tungamirai said: "the party is in crisis and
only a fool can claim otherwise," reported the Zimbabwe News
Agnecy.
</P>
<P>
The youth league natinal assembly session, held at Kushinga
Phikelela College in east Zimbabwe, was attended by President
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Josiah Tungamirai said that for the past three to four years
apathy had enveloped political activity throughout the country so
much that the 1995 general elections and the 1996 presidential
elections were marked by very low turnouts.
</P>
<P>
He said in the rural areas, former liberation war
collaborators were now working to discredit ZANU, leaving party
youths quite uneasy.
</P>
<P>
"As the youth of the party and as future leaders, we find it
quite difficult to fulfil our vanguard role as defenders and
protagonists of ZANU not because of lack of trying but for lack
of any clear vision on where ZANU wants to go," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that factionalism had grown "deep roots" in the party
politburo and had gone down to the cell.
</P>
<P>
He said there was need for soul-searching and self-examination
by the party leadership if they were to understand the magnitude
of the problem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
