<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Syria to Hold Summit on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese and Syrian presidents are
expected to hold talks on Monday in Damascus to discuss Israel's
lastest withdrawal offer from south Lebanon, the official National
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The summit, between Lebanon's Elias Hrawi and Syria's Hafez
al-Assad, will draft a joint counter offensive to confront Israel's
withdrawal offer.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries believe the offer is an
"diplomatic campaign" through which Israel attempted to give the
world an impression that Israel offers to withdraw its troops from
Lebanon while the Beirut government refuses the peace move, the
news agency added.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, Israel inner cabinet formally approved for the
first time in the past 20 years the U.N. Resolution 425, which
calls for an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But it linked the implementation of the resolution with
negotiated security arrangements with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria have firmly rejected the offer, denouncing
it as a "maneuver" aimed at drawing Lebanon into separate
negotiations with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria, which deploys 40,000 troops in
Lebanon, have always insisted that Lebanese and Syrian tracks are
inseparable in peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syrian vice President Abdul Halim Khaddam and Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Sharaa have reportedly flew to Paris and are expected to
meet with French President Jacques Chirac on Sunday for talks on
the Israeli offer. An imminent French initiative on the issue of
south Lebanon will be on the top of the discussions between the
leaders of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said that France has proposed a plan for a
deployment in south Lebanon of 15,000 peace-keeping troops drawn
from France and its former colonies in Africa in the event of the
Israel withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
But there has been no confirmation of the report from any
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in
south Lebanon with the aim of protecting its northern villages and
towns from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israel is also occupying Syria's Golan Heights, which was
captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
