<HEADLINE> Russia, Iran to Join Efforts on Oil Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian acting First Deputy Prime
Minister Boris Nemtsov and Iranian Petroleum Minister Bijan
Namdar-Zanganeh held talks here Saturday on a joint oil policy to
cope with the price crisis, according to the Itar-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister said during the meeting that Tehran
sharply cut its oil production to prevent the prices from further
falling. He called on major oil producers and exporters to follow
its example.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov said, "Russia is interested in improving the state of
the world market but is simultaneously pursuing a consistent
policy of supporting its own oil producers."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Russian government is drawing up measures
to dampen the effects of low oil prices on bigger Russian oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
Russia intends to hold talks with the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) in Moscow this month to hammer out a
coordinated policy on the international oil market, Nemtsov said.
</P>
<P>
Namdar-Zanganeh said that Russian fuel and energy companies
will be granted priority in implementing joint projects on Iranian
territory.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Russia has suffered heavy losses of about
5 trillion U.S. dollars due to the lower oil price in the
international market, so Russian acting Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko on March 25 firmly refused the requirement from OPEC to
reduce its oil production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
