<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Optimistic About S. Leone's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth said Saturday that
it is optimistic about the future of Sierra Leone after an
assessment tour by a team of the 50-strong organization earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
The first proof for it is the quick constitution of a cabinet
by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah following his restoration on
March 10, said a deputy secretary-general of Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the cabinet is trying to reconciliate the various
opinions in the country with opposition leaders, a move which
will help create favorable environment for re-building the
war-ravaged country, the official said, quoted by a British
Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
To assist Sierra Leone's reconstruction, the official said,
the Commonwealth will firstly help the country develop a policy
for the mining sector, especially the diamond industry.
</P>
<P>
Other things need to be done will include the construction of
a sound judicial system, the re-organization of the police force
and the generation of small businesses for profit making.
</P>
<P>
Despite the help of the international community, observers
noted, it is still a daunting job for Kabbah's government to
re-build the country, one of the world's poorest and member of
the Commonwealth, whose development has been stalled by the civil
war since early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The coup, which ousted Kabbah and his government last May, and
the ensuing fightings to overthrow the coupists even led to the
destruction of almost all infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Fighting is still going on in the eastern part of the country
between the west African peacekeeping force ECOMOG and the
remnants of the military junta and allied rebel forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
