<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- France and Lebanon will sign a protocol on developing
Lebanon's agriculture sector, Lebanese newspaper Daily Star
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Agriculture Minister Shawki Fakhoury will leave for
Paris Sunday and is expected to sign the protocol with his French
counterpart Louis le Pensec, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Some 550,000 tourists have visited Lebanon in 1997, a
30 percent increase compared to that of 1996, the Daily Star
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Francesco Frangiali, secretary-general of the World Tourism
Organization, made the announcement at a seminar on Friday called
Tourism Marketing opportunities in the Middle East and North
Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said that most tourists came from neighboring Middle East
countries such as Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, Jordan, Yemen and Syria are among the new tourist
destinations, he said, adding that the Gulf had witnessed a
significant rise in the number of business travelers.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The new terminal of Beirut International Airport
opened on Friday, beginning to cater for 3 million passengers a
year and will double the capacity by the turn of the century, the
newspaper Daily Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 150,000-square-meter new building with 12 departure gates
and 28 different check-in counters was constructed by the German
company Hochtief and the Lebanese firm CCC.
</P>
<P>
The whole project has cost the country 400 million U.S. dollars
during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Tunis -- Tunisia's exports volume in 1997 went up by 14.4
percent to exceed 6,147 million U.S. dollars, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia's imports rose by 16.8 percent to hit 8,756 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
