<HEADLINE> France Cutting Down Troops in Djibouti Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 4 (Xinhua)-- france will cut by more than 20
percent its forces in Djibouti, its main overseas military base,
French Defence Minister Alain Richard said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Richard told Radio France Internationale as he arrived on a
visit to the Republic of Djibouti that French forces would be cut
to 2,600 from 3,300 as part of a general scaling down of military
involvement in Africa, said a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
He said he would discuss the troop cuts and financial
compensation with Djibouti leaders.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, saying that France no
longer wants to be the gendarme of Africa, has ordered cuts in
troops on the continent of about 40 percent to about 5,000 from
8,350, said the report. 
