<HEADLINE> Report: Clinton Says He Has Mixed Feelings about </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
told the upcoming issue of Time magazine that he would have mixed
feelings about the dismissal of Paula Jones's sexual harassment
suit against him.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "If I were just a private citizen, Joe Six-Pack,
I would have mixed feelings about not getting a chance to disprove
these allegations in court. But I don't have mixed feelings as
president, because having the case dismissed and putting this
behind us is plainly in the best interest of the country."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the charges against him in the suit are not true,
adding, "The judge ruled as a matter of law the case had no merit.
And that exposed the raw political nature of this whole
situation."
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Supreme Court case that allowed the Jones
case to proceed while he serves as president, Clinton said, "I
tried as hard as I could to put this and Whitewater in the
smallest possible box and let it be handled by others and to
respond only when required. But now we see why for over 200 years
no one had any idea the president should be subject to a civil
suit and believed that the chances were that if one were filed, it
would have an overwhelming political aspect to it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
