<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Ban Gift-giving to Superiors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet is considering a
ban on gift-giving to superiors or their families in a bid to wipe
out corruption and favoritism, a government source said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is expected to approve the ban at its meeting next
Tuesday, the source said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The ban will require government officials as well as state
enterprise employees to strictly follow the regulations or face
disciplinary action, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The rules, however, do not apply to the social etiquette of
gift-giving or donations. In such a situation, the maximum value
of a gift must not exceed 500 baht (12.5 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The regulation proposed by the Office of the Prime Minister has
been considered by the Civil Service Commission, the Counter
Corruption Commission and the National Culture Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is a follow-up of a cabinet resolution adopted
last year by the previous government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
