<HEADLINE> PNA Asks U.S. to Be Serious With Oslo Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Minister of Trade and
Economy Maher Masri Sunday called on the U.S. to "deal seriously
with" the Oslo accords provisions it brokered between the
Palestinians and Israelis in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with the Egyptian Voice of Arabs Radio
from Nablus in West Bank, Masri criticized a U.S. decision to
postpone revealing a new initiative to break the year-long
deadlock in Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, brought by U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross
to Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu during his recent
shuttling tour of the region, has never been revealed.
</P>
<P>
Masri held Israeli leaders responsible for the fact. "The
Palestinian side has positively dealt with the American
suggestion. The postponement is due to Israel's rejection of the
proposal," Masri told the Cairo-based radio.
</P>
<P>
The proposals have dealt with the transitional stage talks,
implementation of the Israeli troops redeployment along with
avoiding unilateral actions, Israeli settlement expansion in
particular, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Masri urged the Clinton administration to officially declare
the initiative which reportedly stipulates that Israel withdraws
from 13.1 percent of West Bank, accompanied by security
cooperation of the Palestinians. But the proposal was snubbed by
both Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Washington has reportedly backtracked
in the face of pressure of the Jewish lobby in the U.S. Congress
and postponed declaring its Mideast peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was quoted as saying
that Washington would not now declare its idea for reactivating
the peace process and would be content with sustaining its
endeavors without declaring it.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have been stalled for more
than a year over Israeli settlement activities in Arab East
Jerusalem and the long overdue Israeli pullback in West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
