<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Arabs to Protest Police Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Following the Saturday clashes
between Israeli Arabs and police in a northern Israeli Bedouin
village, Israeli Arabs are to hold a general strike Monday to
protest police violence.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made by the Israeli Arabs Supreme Council,
the highest organization of the Israeli Arab citizens.
</P>
<P>
The violent clashes erupted Saturday night in the Sued village
near the northern city of Shfaram when Arab residents threw stones
at police, who tried to demolish three buildings rebuilt without
licenses from Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
Police fired live ammunition and used tear gas and batons to
disperse the rioters. At least a dozen of protesters and 22
policemen were injured in the clashes. About 15 protesters were
detained for interrogation.
</P>
<P>
The clashes triggered strong reaction from Israeli leftist
politicians, as both factions of the Communist Hadash Party and
Meretz party in the Knesset (Parliament) accused the government of
using unnecessary forces in quelling the rioting.
</P>
<P>
The Hadash blasted the police for using "brutal forces"
against Arabs, including live fire and tear gas. It said the
Bedouin residents were only protesting against the demolition of
their houses and their protests had no political or nationalistic
motives.
</P>
<P>
Meretz said the police action on the eve of Muslim feast of the
sacrifice showed the government's insensitivity towards the
sentiments among Israeli Arab citizens.
</P>
<P>
Knesset's Interior Committee announced that it would hold a
special session to discuss the Shfaram clashes. Committee Chairman
Salah Tarif of the leading opposition Labor party said the police
and Interior Ministry's actions on the eve of Muslim holiday were
unnecessary. He warned against sparking a new wave of violence in
the Galilee region, where most of the country's 1 million Israeli
Arabs are living.
</P>
<P>
The clash was one of the worst confrontations between Israeli
troops and Arab Israelis in 20 years, who have been protesting
discrimination and confiscation of properties by Israeli
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Arabs closely associate with the Palestinians in
the territories and support their struggle against Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, Arabs across Israel observed a general strike and
held protests to mark the Land Day dedicated to six Arabs killed
in a protest against Israel's confiscation of land in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
