<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Iran Exchange More POWs for Third Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A new batch of 1,500 Iraqi
prisoners of war (POWs) released by Iran have returned to their
homeland, the Iraqi News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency said Iraq, in a reciprocal measure, released 89
Iranian detainees captured during the eight-year Iran-Iraq war
(1980-88) in the latest POW exchange.
</P>
<P>
A swap ceremony, the third in four days, was held Saturday
evening and supervised by the International Committee of the Red
Cross (ICRC) at the border city of al-Mundhariya.
</P>
<P>
In the past three days, Iran set free two batches of about
1,800 Iraqi POWs, and Iraq released 112 Iranians under scheduled
program agreed on by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that in this biggest release of POWs
since 1991, Iran will release nearly 5,600 Iraqis in exchange
for 380 Iranian prisoners held by Iraq. In 1990, the two
countries exchanged 39,000 POWs.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been accusing each other of holding
POWs, which had remained a major obstacle to the resumption of
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
During the bloody war in the 1980s, an estimated 1 million
Iranians and Iraqis were killed or wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
