<DOCNO> XIE19980405.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Global Bonds Over-subscribed: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The floating of 500 million dollars
of 10-year Philippine Global Bonds was over-subscribed at its
launching on April 2, indicating investors' continued confidence
in the Philippine economy, a senior official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum published here, Finance Secretary Salvador
Enriquez Jr. said that the bonds, priced at 337.5 basis points
above the 10-year U.S. treasuries, compared favorably with a
similar issue by Brazil, which is now trading at 385 basis points.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine bonds issue is expected to be better priced than
a forthcoming issue by South Korea, which is anticipated to be
priced within the range of 350 and 400 basis points, Enriquez
said.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said the Philippine bonds issue is significant because
"it made the Philippines the first Asian country to access the
voluntary capital markets after the eruption of the currency
turmoil."
</P>
<P>
The floating of the bonds raised a significant amount of
resources from institutional investors (not banks), many of whom
are investing in the Philippines for the first time, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It will open up access by Philippine infrastructure projects
to new sources of financing in the future," said the secretary.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said that the bonds will relieve pressure on domestic
interest rates and boost international reserves, which will
enhance financial stability.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said the favorable pricing and long maturity manifest
investors' strong confidence in the continuity of economic reforms
and recognition of the resilience of the Philippine economy amid
the on-going currency turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
