<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Jordan to Joint Hands in Water Conservancy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- In a joint venture designed to
strengthen its ties with Jordan, Israel has agreed in principle to
allow Lack Galilee to act as a reservoir for water from a river in
Jordan, local daily Haaretz reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Jordan will then be able to use more
effectively the water from the Yarmouk River, which lies near the
Israeli-Jordanian border.
</P>
<P>
However, Jordan will not be able to draw out more water than
it diverted from the Yarmouk in any one year. As a result, the
project will not lead to any net change in Israel's water supply.
</P>
<P>
In order to implement the project without overflowing the lake,
Israel will divert water from the upper Jordan River, which is
currently the main source of the lake, to a pipeline that will
carry it to the National Water Carrier.
</P>
<P>
The report said that negotiations on the project were
conducted in secret over the past months, with the initiative
coming from both Jordan and Israel's water commissions.
</P>
<P>
The final understanding between the two countries was reached
during the visit of Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan to Israel on
March 10. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu gave his
consent to the project even though initially he had doubts about
its diplomatic ramification. Planning and engineering work will
begin soon.
</P>
<P>
Israelis' reactions to the understanding have been mixed,
especially in the defense establishment and among water experts.
</P>
<P>
Opponents charged that Israel has inappropriately given a third
party direct access to Lake Galilee, a crucial strategic reservoir.
</P>
<P>
They predicted that Jordan will increasingly request more
water to help alleviate its chronic shortages. According to this
view, a dangerous mutual dependence is liable to develop,
ultimately giving rise to conflicts despite the original good
intentions.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, advocates of the plan said that the project
will draw Israel and Jordan closer together. Assistance to Jordan
will facilitate cooperation in other spheres as well, and the
water pact will be presented as one of the fruits of the peace
treaty signed in 1994 between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, experts said that diverting water from the upper
Jordan River into the National Water Carrier will reduce water
prices in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Instead of pumping the water up from Lake Galilee, which is 209
meters below sea level, water will be taken from the upper Jordan,
which is 150 meters above the sea level, thus enabling the water
to flow by force of gravity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
