<HEADLINE> World Health Day Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh observed the World Health
Day Sunday, underlining the importance of "safe motherhood."
</P>
<P>
President Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
issued separate messages on the eve of the occasion.
</P>
<P>
"It is of utmost importance to ensure service deliveries to
pregnant women to reduce the mortality rate," the president said
in his message.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister in her message underscored the need for
strengthening the health education campaign to reduce the mother
and child mortality rates in the country.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Day falls on April 7, but it was observed in
Bangladesh on Sunday because of the three-day Eid-ul-Azha, the
second biggest festival for the Moslems, starting from next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Bangladesh, 92 percent of childbirth take place at home,
according to the WHO (the World Health Organization)
representative in the country.
</P>
<P>
Though the technology for safe birth was available, but it was
not accessible due to ignorance and poverty. Therefore, child
mortality per 1,000 living is as high as 76.8, the official figure
shows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
