<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000 Mozambican Refugees Demand to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 Somali refugees
staying in northern Kenya, claiming that they were Mozambican
descendants, demand to return to their ancestral homeland in
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The refugees said their forefathers had been taken to Somalia
from northern Mozambique as slaves.
</P>
<P>
But the Mozambican government find it hard to decide whether
to agree to allow them to go back to Mozambique, Domingo, the
Sunday paper published here said today.
</P>
<P>
"It is still too early for the government to make any
prediction (for the refugees' fate)," Fernando Fazenda, director
at the Refugee Assistance Center, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Fazenda, who had ever visited some refugee camps in Kenya with
a delegation, said that some of the refugees are characterized
with apparent Mozambican culture, with some of them able to speak
the dialect in northern Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
He said the plight of the refugees, who are treated as cheap
labors, is very hard, but the Mozambican government has to
consider the issue very carefully before making any decision, as
they might be a heavy burden to the country.
</P>
<P>
Once Mozambique decided to receive these refugees, he said,
the international society should shoulder the responsibility of
assisting in their settlement to ease the pressure upon
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Fazenda noted that his country still faces the problem of
settling about two million dismobilized military personnel, war
refugees and dislodged people during the civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
