<HEADLINE> China's Service Trade Developing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China's international service
trade has grown at an average annual rate of 15.4 percent in the
last two decades, higher than the world's average.
</P>
<P>
China's service trade volume surged from 5.54 billion
U.S. dollars in 1982 to 43.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1995,
according to the International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
China's service trade has kept pace with merchandise trade, the
paper reported, which has helped promote their mutual development.
</P>
<P>
The development of China's international service trade has been
based on the surging service sector since China initiated the
reform and opening-up policy two decades ago, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of China's service sector in its gross domestic
product (GDP) shot up from 20 percent in 1982 to 30.7 percent in
1995, and the service sector has grown by an average annual rate
of 11.2 percent in this period, 0.6 percent higher than that of
the GDP, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted 1996 statistics showing that China's
service exports were 19.62 billion U.S. dollars, mainly from
tourism, banking and cargo transportation services. The import
figure for 1996 was 21.36 billion U.S. dollars, mainly from cargo
transportation, banking and tourism services.
</P>
<P>
China's major service trade partners are Hong Kong, Japan and
the United States, the newspaper reported, adding that China's
service trade also shifted from a trade surplus to a deficit.
</P>
<P>
At present, China's has eight categories of international
service trade: cargo transportation, insurance, port supply and
labor services, tourism, banking, posts and telecommunications,
contracting for labor services and governmental exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
