<DOCNO> XIE19980405.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. African Army Chief of Staff Has to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Georg Meiring, the chief of
staff of the South African National Defense Force (SANDF), has
been given two choices: resign or be fired, the newspaper City
Press quoted unidentified sources as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meiring has been facing sharp criticism from the government
for days after he handed President Nelson Mandela a report
compiled by the Military Intelligence (MI), alleging senior
members of the African National Congress (ANC) were plotting a
coup against the government.
</P>
<P>
A top-level government team, consisting of several key
ministers, has met with Meiring to convey the govenrment's
decision that he should either step down himself or be fired.
</P>
<P>
The team consisted of Defense Minister Joe Modise, his deputy
Ronnie Kasril, Minister of Justice and Intelligence Dullah Omar
and Mandela's senior legal advisor Fink Haysom.
</P>
<P>
Meiring was authorized by the Government of National Unity
headed by Mandela to take up the job in 1994, when the first
non-racial general elections in South Africa took place.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources revealed at the weekend that a package has
already been worked out for Meiring. The government team was
scheduled to discuss with Meiring what he would receive if he
chose to voluntarily resign, and what he would receive if he was
fired.
</P>
<P>
An announcement is expected to be made before Wednesday next
week on the decision after Meiring has given the government team
a response.
</P>
<P>
The order calling for Meiring to resign or be fired came after
senior SANDF generals made a similar call to Mandela when they
met with him last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the generals, who had distinguished military
experience and are held in high esteem by their former liberation
armies, are said to have been identified in the Meiring report as
being part of the coup plotters.
</P>
<P>
The report claimed that SANDF chief of staff Lieutenant
General Siphiwe Nyanda was among the coup plotters. Other
conspirator, whose names have not been made public, are said to
include all the ex-Umkonto we Sizwe (MK) cadres who now occupy
the most senior positions in the SANDF.
</P>
<P>
MK was the military wing of the ANC before it took over state
power in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The generals who met Mandela are said to have expressed
misgivings about any future working relationship with Meiring in
the SANDF.
</P>
<P>
They also called on Mandela to get rid of the entire staff of
the MI, which made up largely of elements from the previous
regime. MI was still haunted by the past and is resisting and
even sabotaging change, the generals said.
</P>
<P>
One general described the MI as "rotten to the core" and
"unreformable."
</P>
<P>
In meeting with the generals, Mandela reportedly said that he
did not doubt the loyalty of any of the senior members of the
armed forces who had been implicated in the MI report which
claims there was a plot against the government.
</P>
<P>
Local press said the decision to dissolve the MI is a
political matter and can only be carried out by Mandela. It is
inconceivable that the president will ignore the calls of the
generals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
