<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Changes to Be Made for Table Tennis in Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, Jiangsu Province, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The format for
the table tennis competition will be changed in the 2000 Sydney
Olympic Games, Adham Sharara, vice president of the International
Table Tennis Federation (ITTF) announced in a press conference
here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Among the 64 players for each of the singles events, 16 seeds
will receive a bye in the round-robin group competition, in which
the other 48 will be drawn in 16 groups, Sharara said after a
three-day ITTF conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the 16 group leaders then join the seeds to play the
make-or-break playoffs from the second round.
</P>
<P>
The 43 pairs for every doubles events will also fight on a
similar format, with the eight seeds skipping the first round and
the others vying for the remaining eight second-round places
through group competitions.
</P>
<P>
The singles players will qualify for the Olympic Games through
four channels.
</P>
<P>
The top 20 in the latest ITTF rankings will qualify
automatically, but one country or region can only have two at the
most for each event.
</P>
<P>
Another 40 players will come out through four continental
qualifiers, with 11 places for Asia and Europe apiece, six for
Latin America and Africa three respectively and three each for
North America and Oceania.
</P>
<P>
Three berths will be given in a world qualifying competitions
for the losers in their own continental meets. And the final one
will be awarded to the host nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
