<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pohang Steelers Wins AFC Club Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A controversial second try in
the decisive penalty shoot-out brought South Korea's defending
champion Pohang Steelers to a 6-5 win over China's Dalian Wanda in
the final and the crown of the 17th Asian Football Confederation
(AFC) Club Championship here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time in the championship's history that a
team has won the title for two consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
Wanda and Steelers tied at 5-5 after the sixth round
shoot-out. Wu Jun missed the seventh shot for the Dalian club. And
the first attempt by Abbas Jassim, an Iraqi international playing
for the South Korean club, was ruled by the referee a foul before
he made the shot, which he also missed. Jassim shot again and
scored to seal a narrow win for the South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
Dalian Wanda's defender Zhang Enhua refused to take the most
valuable player award, which was announced for him after the
match. He was believed to face disciplinary actions from both the
Chinese Football Association and the AFC.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier match, Al Hilal of Saudi Arabia beat Pirouzi of
Iran 4-1 to take the third place.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Aldosari of Saudi Arabia's Al Hilal team was named the
most valuable player of the championship and Pohang Steelers' Jeon
Kyeong Joon was announced as the event's highest scorer with seven
goals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
