<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization of Zambian Copper Mines Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Economics Association of
Zambia (EAZ) has criticized the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) for its way of privatizing its mines, alleging that the
exercise lacks a clear vision.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Times of Zambia quoted EAZ Chairman Moses Banda as
charging that the whole issue of privatization lacks a clear
concept of the objectives, methodology of disposal and a vision
of what privatization entails.
</P>
<P>
Banda said in statement released here that as far as ZCCM
privatization is concerned the bundling of assets in packages
leaves the government to the whims of the bidders who have formed
consortiums which in turn weaken Zambia's bargaining position.
</P>
<P>
Big packages only encourage large bidders to dictate the
terms, he said.
</P>
<P>
Banda said since mid 1997 the government and a ZCCM
negotiating team have assured all interested parties that a
favorable agreement is in the offing. However, the association is
at the same time not surprised at the turn of events.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the best option will be to put ZCCM under a
private management contract, a measure which will give confidence
to the lenders and even the share-holders.
</P>
<P>
He also said that in the next wave of privatization, the
remaining companies and divisions should further be unbundled and
be given private management contracts.
</P>
<P>
Banda made the criticism and suggestion after negotiations on
sale of Zambia's two biggest copper mines collapsed recently.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on the sale of Nchanga and Nkana mines have
collapsed due to disagreements between the Kafue Consortium and
the ZCCM privatization team.
</P>
<P>
Last month Falconbridge, a leading Canadian mining company
pulled out of the Konkola deep project consortium, citing lower
copper price as the reason for the pull-out.
</P>
<P>
Due to copper price falls in the international market and
outdated equipment, lack of investment and mismanagement, the
annual copper output of Zambia, one of the biggest
copper-producing countries in the world, has decreased gradually
to about 300,000 tons in recent years.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investments, advanced technology and
management to revive the stagnating copper production, the
government has invited foreign tenders for the ZCCM mines and
assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
