<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU-Nigeria Relation Facing Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The unnoticed withdrawal of the
head of the European Union (EU) mission in Nigeria has indicated
that the cold relationship between Nigeria and members of the
Union is far from thawing.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, there is no sign of a soon-to-arrive
replacement of Jeremy Tunnacliffe, the head of the mission, who
left Nigeria on March 16 without ceremonies for his new post in
Bosnia, mission sources here said over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
According to the Guardian paper Sunday, even top officials at
the EU mission here were taken by surprise as they got hint of
Tunnacliffe's recall by the headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"He worked normally the previous day but the next day we were
hurriedly called in for the hand-over," an official said.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the EU might not send in a new envoy until
the Nigerian government makes real its pronounced commitment to
hand over to civil rule and uphold the tenets of human rights
initially by the release of political detainees.
</P>
<P>
EU aids to Nigeria were suspended in November 1995 shortly
after the hanging of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni minority
activists.
</P>
<P>
The execution also led to the suspension of Nigeria's
membership in the Commonwealth and sanctions against the west
African country.
</P>
<P>
The European parliament is already pushing for stiffer
sanctions against Nigeria if a genuine transition to civil rule
does not occur by October this year.
</P>
<P>
The measures considered include a total arms embargo, a
provision forbidding the sponsorship of trade missions to Nigeria
by EU member states, maintaining current sanctions against and
freezing financial assets held in the EU by the Nigerian
government, top government officials and their families.
</P>
<P>
It might be a result of the frosty relations that
ambassadors-designate appointed by the Nigerian government to
some of these European countries were being delayed from
presenting their letters of credence on many occasions, according
to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
