<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Rules out Imminent Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's presidential political
advisor Osama el-Baz has ruled out the convening of an Arab summit
in the near future, the Middle East News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of the summit, not the summit per se, is what
counts," Baz said in an interview with a program of the local Nile
TV aired Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
El-Baz said that Arab leaders will not hesitate to call a
summit "if it might really serve the Arab cause in a specific
point or augment the Arab rights in a definite area."
</P>
<P>
His statement came amid ripe speculation that efforts were
underway for an Arab mini-summit before the end of this month to
take stock of the year-long deadlock in peace-making and chart the
future course of Arab solidarity. Cairo hosted the last Arab
summit in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
The anticipation was fueled by a meeting in Riyadh last Monday
of foreign ministers of Egypt, Syria and Saudi Arabia as well as
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, after American Middle East
peace envoy Dennis Ross once again failed to bridge the gap
between Israel and the Palestinian to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Arab capitals are looking forward to the revelation of the
U.S. apocalyptic proposal in order to thaw the frozen peace
process," el-Baz said, hoping that the U.S. administration will
disclose the initiative by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. policy-making team is giving finishing touches on the
initiative in light of Ross' latest tour in the region, according
to el-Baz, who is believed to be the brain behind Egypt's foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
El-Baz also tentatively set Thursday or Friday as when the
U.S. initiative might be unleashed. Washington reportedly wants
Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the West Bank, in exchange
for security cooperation from the Palestinians. But both Israel
and the Palestinians were cool to the idea.
</P>
<P>
In favor of the fresh U.S. efforts to unblock the peace
deadlock, Egypt urged the U.S. to come up with a formal initiative
which it said must be "balanced and consistent with signed
agreements."
</P>
<P>
El-Baz said "neither (Israeli Prime Minister) Benjamin
Netanyahu nor any person of his like can threaten the
U.S. administration." He was referring to the Netanyahu's attempt
to lobby Jewish friends in the American Congress against the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian official further called upon the U.S. to formulate
a mechanism that would put the initiative into action, saying that
application of any agreement or initiative is more important than
the initiative itself, whether it is "an American or a European
one."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled for more
than a year over Israeli construction of a new settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem and long-delayed military pullback in the West
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
