<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Longest Suspension Bridge Opens to Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The 3,911-meter Akashi Kaikyo
Bridge, the world's longest suspension bridge, opened to traffic
Sunday afternoon in Western Japan, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the opening of the bridge, which connects Kobe and
Awaji Island, both in Hyogo Prefecture, Western Japan, ceremonies
were held at both ends of the bridge with about 1,300 guests
attending, including Japan's Crown Prince Naruhito and Princess
Masako.
</P>
<P>
The new bridge, which measures 1,991 meters between its two
towers, exceeds the previous record of 1,410 meters that the
Humber Estuary Bridge in Humberside, Britain, had held since
opening in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The motor-vehicles-only bridge completes the 89-kilometer
Kobe-Awaji-Naruto Expressway connecting Kobe and Naruto in
Tokushima Prefecture on the western Japanese main island of
Shikoku.
</P>
<P>
It costs some 500 billion yen (about 3.8 billion dollars) to
build the bridge. Work started in May 1988.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles can now travel between Kobe and Tokushima in 100
minutes, compared with three hours by ferry.
</P>
<P>
Developers said they expect the bridge to lure tourists from
the Kinki region, which includes Japan's second largest city of
Osaka, to Shikoku and Awaji Island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
