<HEADLINE> Jordan: Killing Hamas Leader Hampers Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official has said
that the killing of the Islamic Resistance Movement's (Hamas)
leader Muhei Eddine Sharif in the West Bank city Ramallah would
hamper the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Jordan Times newspaper Sunday quoted Deputy
Prime Minister and Minister of Information Abdullah Ensour as
saying that "the episode of assassination and counter
assassination irrespective of its source is a matter that
contributes to the stalemate in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
"We call upon all the parties to live up to their commitments
to reach a just solution that will guarantee peace for all,"
Ensour said.
</P>
<P>
He urged Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to
implement the agreements signed with the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) to spare the region an escalation of tension.
</P>
<P>
"Partial solutions or any delay in implementing them,
especially those agreed upon publicly, will lead to nothing but
more violence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan denounced "terrorism" no matter what its "sources or
excuses" were, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, a leader of the Izzaddin Kassam, the military wing of
Hamas, was shot dead before his body was dumped into a car that
exploded last Sunday in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Hamas blamed Israel for the assassination and vowed to avenge
the death of Sharif with blood-shed. But Israel denied the charge
against it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
