<HEADLINE> Microsoft May Invest in Israeli Venture Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The global software giant
Microsoft is being tempted into dabbling its virtual toes in
venture capital by an Israeli investment company, local daily
Haaretz reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Israeli company Aura Investments Research
and Development is negotiating to bring Microsoft and other
companies into a special venture capital fund as strategic and
financial investors.
</P>
<P>
The fund, which has already reached an advanced stage of
raising capital, is intended to manage a volume of between 60
million and 80 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
If the negotiations are successfully concluded, it will mark
the first time Microsoft has ever invested in any venture capital
endeavor. Until now, Microsoft has confined itself to direct
investments by taking over high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
At this stage, the scope of investment by Microsoft and the
other companies in the fund is not clear. However, local capital
market sources predict that the total volume of the fund will be
larger than originally anticipated if Microsoft joins in.
</P>
<P>
According to the definitions set by Aura, the new venture fund
will invest in Israeli companies engaged mainly in
Internet-related technology and multimedia companies.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Steve Ballmer, Microsoft's executive vice
president for sales and supports and one of the company's
dominant figures, is expected to visit Israel within a few weeks,
apparently to continue the talks with Aura.
</P>
<P>
Ballmer is supervising Microsoft's side for the negotiations
on investment in the Aura venture capital fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
