<HEADLINE> Egypt to Pardon 1,200 Prisoners in Greater Bairam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- About 1,200 prisoners will be freed
on Tuesday as Egypt starts to celebrate the Greater Bairam, or the
feast of the sacrifice in the Islamic world, the Egyptian Gazette
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the English-language newspaper, all those to be
released must have served at least half of their sentences and
have a record of good conduct during imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
But those convicts for crimes related to immorality, terrorism
and drugs are not eligible to the seasonal pardon.
</P>
<P>
An official source at the Prisons Department told reporters
Saturday that on the first day of the four-day feast, prisoners
will be allowed to meet scholars and theologians from Al Azhar,
the most prestigious seat for Islamic learning, to discuss
religious and cultural matters.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the exceptional visits allowed, a number of
entertainment programs will also be organized for the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
This will be Egypt's second amnesty in less than three months.
Altogether 1,600 prisoners were set free on January 29 under the
same conditions on the occasion of the Lesser Bairam following the
Muslim holy month of Ramadan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
