<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Expects PNA to Clear Its Name in Sharif's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel is expecting the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to clear its name in the
alleged assassination of Hamas bombmaker Muhei Eddine Sharif,
Israel Radio reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has promised to publish the results of its probe into
the mysterious death of Sharif, whose deformed body was found
inside a car that exploded last Sunday in the West Bank city
Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Israel hopes the PNA investigation would exonerate its alleged
involvement in Sharif's death so as to reduce the motivation of
Islamic Resistance Movement for launching terror attacks against
it.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has blamed Israeli agents for killing Sharif before
blowing up the car to cover up the murder. It vowed to avenge
Sharif's killing by carrying out suicide attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
But the militant group is also suspecting that Palestinian
police might have carried out the assassination in collaboration
with Israel. Hamas leader in Gaza Abdel Rantisi hinted Saturday
that Sharif was arrested and tortured to death by the Palestinian
security forces before they used the car bombing to cover up the
killing.
</P>
<P>
The PNA originally held Israel responsible for murdering
Sharif, but it later revised the position following Israel's
strong denial of any involvement.
</P>
<P>
Israeli General Security Service head Ami Ayalon and Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's attorney Yithzak Molcho have met
secretly with PNA President Yasser Arafat in Gaza Strip to drive
home that Israel had nothing to do with the killing.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu warned Friday that Israel would hold the PNA
responsible for any Hamas attacks if it continued accusing Israel
of plotting the murder.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday, the PNA Cabinet said it is now
investigating the possibility that Sharif was killed by other
Hamas members due to inner split.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has reportedly been trying to placate Hamas to forestall
terror attacks against Israel, fearing Israel could find excuses
to torpedo the already stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has so far rejected the PNA's claim on Hamas' inner feud
and the demand for restraint, vowing to avenge the death of Sharif
with blood-shed.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Hamas rally in Gaza Saturday, Rantisi called on
Hamas' military wing Izzedin Kassim, which is responsible for the
past suicide bombings in Israel, to continue its struggle against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have been on high alert to guard
against possible terror attacks by Hamas, which has suspended
operations against Israel since its spiritual leader and founder
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin was released from Israeli jail last October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
