<HEADLINE> Bilharzia Threatens Zambian Villagers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,000 villagers in Kafue
district near Lusaka risk developing urinary and liver
complications because bilharzia, Sunday Times of Zambia reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The national newspaper quoted Kafue district director of
health Dyness Kasungami who has conducted a health survey of the
Lishiko area of the district as saying the bilharzia in the area
is endemic.
</P>
<P>
She said villagers are drawing water for domestic use from
ponds in which they bathe, urinate and defecate, making it
difficult for the disease to be controlled.
</P>
<P>
People in the area have lived with bilharzia for a long time
but are not aware of the long term consequences, she said.
</P>
<P>
Kasungami said that the only way to eradicate the disease is
to ensure that villagers have proper toilets and safe water
supply because treating the disease alone is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from treatment, it is important to have good sanitation
and safe sources of water," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Treatment is very expensive and not the answer, so we need to
come up with prevention and control measures," she said.
</P>
<P>
At Lishiko primary school many pupils are reported to have
blood in their urine.
</P>
<P>
The pupils swim in snail infested ponds catching bilharzia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
