<DOCNO> XIE19980405.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Step to Correct S. African Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- South African prisoners will
be put to work building houses and roads under armed guards in
poor areas, national newspaper Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners will be paid, but, in turn, will have to pay for
their food and prison accommodation. Some of their money will
also have to be donated to crime victims, Correctional Services
Minister Sipo Mzimela was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mzimela launched the nationwide project Friday, with the
laying of the first bricks in a 22-house development south of
Durban, a port city in east of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said it was hoped that criminals would learn skills which
they could use after their release. "We are trying this
innovative program to reduce the high rate of prisoners turning
back to crime once they have been released."
</P>
<P>
The plan, which will begin in other provinces before the end
of the year, will eventually see thousands of supervised
volunteer artisan-convicts working.
</P>
<P>
Mzimela said the public should not feel threatened because no
dangerous prisoners would be allowed out on the work gangs.
Instead, only prisoners who were not violent, who were sentenced
for petty offenses, who were model prisoners or who had served
most of their sentences would get the work opportunity.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a very powerful weapon to fight crime and it is
very important for society to accept these prisoners."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that working prisoners would fall under the
provisions of the Labor Relations Act and would be allowed to
organize themselves into unions.
</P>
<P>
"Their training will be done by correctional services staff
free of charge, but once they are engaged in real productive
work, they will be paid like regular workers," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
