<HEADLINE> New Committee Urged for Zimbabwe's Mine Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Associated Mine Workers' Union
of Zimbabwe is agitating for the formation of a high-powered gold
crisis committee to deal with the continued collapse of mines.
</P>
<P>
President of the union, Jefrey Mutnadare said at the weekend
that the envisaged committee should bring together the three
social partners -- employers, workers and the government, the
Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
It would have a mandate to deal with all mine retrenchments
and try to come up with alternatives before a mine is closed and
workers retrenched.
</P>
<P>
It was also being anticipated that this committee would be
able to come up with a social plan to help the retrenched
workers.
</P>
<P>
Up to 5,000 workers had been laid off since world prices of
gold and other minerals began tumbling about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The suppressed prices were said to have been triggered by
European Reserve Banks that had stockpiled huge reserves of gold
in their bank vaults.
</P>
<P>
It is not known when the prices were likely to pick up again.
Until this happens, the wave of mine closures and retrenchments
was expected to continue, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Just this year alone, three major mines in Zimbabwe closed
while several others had either retrenched or announced they
would be doing so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
