<HEADLINE> 200,000 Bangladeshis Affected by Cancer Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- About 200,000 people are affected by
cancer every year in Bangladesh, and 150,000 of them die, press
reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The total number of cancer patients in this South Asian nation
now exceeds 800,000, reports said, quoting World Health
Organization statistics.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the cancer cases in the country were due to
use of tobacco and tobacco products, so the extent of cancer could
be contained by about half through discarding tobacco, Bangladesh
Cancer Society (BCS) vice-president Prof. M.A. Hye said at a
conference in Dhaka Saturday.
</P>
<P>
More emphasis should be given on primary prevention as
diagnosis at the initial stage, he said, pointing out that
treatment facilities in the country "are inadequate."
</P>
<P>
BCS president Prof. Syed Fazlul Haq told the conference that
mass media, including radio, TV and newspapers, could play an
important role in raising awareness among people and educating
them on cancer.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the conference, Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria
said the government would not allow revenue earning through the
use of tobacco at the cost of public health.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that revenue earning is very important for a
country like ours, but new sources can be dug out if one source is
closed," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister called for creating mass awareness against
smoking through social mobilization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
