<HEADLINE> Trade With Myanmar at some Thai Checkpoints Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Exports of goods to Myanmar
through border checkpoints in four districts of Thailand's
northern province of Tak were temporarily suspended starting from
Sunday, news reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The suspension is aimed at preventing security problems caused
by fighting in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Security forces were reportedly dispatched to border areas of
the four districts to ensure there would be no deliveries of goods
within three km of the border.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, six border checkpoints in another district of the
province remained open to cross-border trade.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post quoted a military officer as saying that the
current border situation was not good for cross-border trade due
to fighting between Myanmar troops and guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The officer said the measure would be enforced temporarily
until the situation improves and the safety of Thai exporters and
customs officials could be ensured.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has worked out a western seaboard development project
in an effort to boost border trade with Myanmar and other
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
However, there are concerns that the opening of checkpoints to
border trade would pose a threat to national security. Some state
agencies expressed fears that the opening of checkpoints would
encourage the influx of Myanmar immigrants into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
They also said these immigrants might bring with them
contagious diseases such as tuberculosis, elephantiasis, syphilis,
malaria and leprosy.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's suspension of border trade through checkpoints
reflected these concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
