defend his Japan Grand Prix win, but retired with about seven
laps to go due to engine trouble.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 All Japan 250cc champion Daijiro Kato on Honda used
his pole position and jumped to an early lead in the 250cc
category and hung on to win over three fellow Japanese riders in
a pack of four about 25 seconds ahead of the next group of
riders.
</P>
<P>
Shinya Nakano on Yamaha took second and Naoki Matsudo, also
on Yamaha, came in third.
</P>
<P>
Japanese riders swept the 125cc category with Kazuto Sakata
on Aprilia edging out Tomomi Manako on Honda and Masao Azuma
also on Honda, who took second and third respectively. 
