<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Experiencing "Cancerous Scourges": </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said the ruling Zanu (PF) is now experiencing"cancerous scourges"
of unguarded ambitions, deviationism, factionalism, regionalism
and tribalism.
</P>
<P>
As guest speaker at the Zanu Youth League National Assembly
meeting at Kushinga Phikelela Training College in east Zimbabwe
Saturday, Mugabe, who is also first secretary of the ruling
party, urged youths to shun divisive tendencies which he said
were being promoted by some senior members in the party
hierarchy, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said he wondered where the youth of Zimbabwe, renowned
for their vigilance were while what he termed infiltrators and
divisive elements wreaked havoc on the unity and oneness of Zanu.
</P>
<P>
In his welcoming remarks, Zanu Secretary for Youth Affairs,
retired Air Chief Marshal Josiah Tungamirai, told Mugabe that it
was now difficult for the party's youth league to mobilize the
people because all there was to offer was a "glorified past and
empty promises" for the future.
</P>
<P>
However, Mugabe urged the youth to continue to be loyal,
vigilant and energetic in their efforts to revitalize the party
and its organs.
</P>
<P>
The president also referred to the recent food riots which
turned violent and said that it was absolutely critical for the
youth to recognize that as a nation, Zimbabweans should strive to
resolve their problems and differences peacefully through dialog.
</P>
<P>
"The youth should shun destructive strikes and demonstrations
that often degenerate into lawlessness, looting and destruction
of property," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
