<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strict Inspections of Imports, Exports Promotes Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China's commodity inspection
departments have strengthened control of the quality of imported and
exported goods to promote the country's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
While strictly prohibiting exporters from shipping fake and
unqualified goods, China is striving to keep foreign traders from
bringing unqualified products into the country, said officials
from the State Administration of Inspection of Import and Export
Commodities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the administration show that China's commodity
inspection departments checked 2.31 million batches of import and
export commodities in 1997 valued at 108 billion U.S. dollars, up
22.7 percent and 18 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The departments have adopted strict rules for the inspection of
imported waste and ordered traders to have their imports inspected
both prior to shipment and at the first port of arrival. And 117
harmful shipments were discovered in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Administration officials said improved product quality has
guaranteed the country's healthy and steady foreign trade
development.
</P>
<P>
They said the whole commodity inspection system has 46,000 sets
of advanced inspection equipment valued at 1.36 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
