<DOCNO> XIE19980405.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surtax Levied on Big Earners in Slovak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Empowered by a new law, the Slovak
government is imposing a surtax on the country's some 2,000
"millionaires" -- in the sense of local currency.
</P>
<P>
Effective Wednesday, the new tax of up to 30 percent on annual
incomes of over one million koruny, or about 33,300 U.S. dollars,
is an effort to narrow the gap between the rich and the poor.
</P>
<P>
A 10 percent surtax is for earnings between 1.27 million koruny
(38,500 dollars) and 4 million koruny (120,000 dollars), and a 20
percent rate is for those up to 9 million koruny (270,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
As called for by the legislation approved recently by the
parliament, the highest rate of 30 percent is reserved for annual
incomes even higher, the newspaper Economic News reported.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, as shown by 1997 official statistics, per capita
income of the country's active labor force was 9,226 koruny (280
dollars) a month, or 110,712 koruny (3,360 dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
The new measure is expected to generate some 200 million koruny
(6 million dollars) additional tax revenues for the state
coffers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980405.0124 </DOCNO>
