<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fires Cause Alarm in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 3,488 forest fires occurred
in Costa Rica in the first quarter of this year and destroyed over
9,800 hectares of forests and ecological reserves.
</P>
<P>
The figure, as shown by statistics released by the Environment
and Energy Ministry, is alarming, since there were a total of only
3,773 fires of the kind across the country last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said there was a daily average of 39 emergency
calls in the first three months of the year reporting bush fires
caused by persons who burned grass in the very dry season.
</P>
<P>
The areas where more fires occurred are the country's northeast
and northwest. For example, fires destroyed 1,800 hectares of
conservation in Guanacaste, and 3,500 hectares in Filadelfia.
</P>
<P>
"We are about to enter a critical period for parks and
protected areas," said Environment and Energy Minister Rene Castro.
</P>
<P>
Castro said the government was developing a plan of action to
deal with the current drought caused by the El Nino weather
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's forest law calls for up to three years in
prison for those who purposely set fires to forest, and for fines
to be imposed on those who cause forest fires accidentally.
</P>
<P>
Another problem, he said, is there are people who take
advantage of the fires to illegally hunt animals fleeing from
forest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
