<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Grant Trial Licenses To Foreign Insurance Brokers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China is considering granting
operating licenses to one or two foreign insurance brokerage
companies, according to today's China Daily (Business Weekly).
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a senior official of the People's Bank of
China (PBOC) as saying that those licensed will be encouraged to
set up joint venture companies in China.
</P>
<P>
He said a detailed plan determining the business scale and
geographical restrictions is still in the process of elaboration.
</P>
<P>
As China is a latecomer to the insurance brokerage industry, it
is necessary to proceed gradually in choosing foreign insurance
brokers to introduce advanced management techniques, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the British Sedgwick Group entered China in the early
1980s, more than a dozen foreign insurance brokers have opened
representative offices.
</P>
<P>
Although representative offices are non-profit institutions
prohibited from undertaking broking business, some are engaged
covertly, according to industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
Such activities leave clients with their rights unprotected, and
they also create headaches for the insurance watchdog and are a
cause of tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Selectively granting licenses to some brokers will be conducive
to standardizing the market and promoting the growth of the
domestic brokerage industry, according to expert opinion.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's move to consider opening the insurance
brokerage market follows the promulgation of the experimental
regulation on insurance broker management in February this year.
</P>
<P>
Freeman Zhang, chief representative of the Beijing office of UK
firm Willis Corroon China Ltd, said his company is preparing its
application for the operating license. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
