<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Suspends, But Not Liquidates Ailing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (central bank)
Governor Syahril Sabirin said the suspension of a number of banks
does not mean they had been liquidated.
</P>
<P>
"They were merely told to stop operating, not to close their
offices," Syahril said after joining a meeting with International
Monetary Fund (IMF) officials here Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday Afternoon, Finance Minister Fuad Bawazier announced
the suspension of seven private commercial banks and placing of
another seven under the management of the Indonesian Bank
Restructuring Agency (IBRA). They include Bank Danamon, Bank
Dagang Nasional Indonesia and Bank Ekspor-Impor Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"These decisions are part of the ongoing national banking
reforms to restore its reputation and regain the confidence of
people at home and abroad," Fuad said.
</P>
<P>
"They are part of an overall strategy of restoring our economy,
and they are part of our efforts to strengthen the rupiah's
exchange rate," the finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
Syahril also told depositors of the frozen banks not to worry
about the possibility of losing their savings. "The obligations of
the banks concerned to their customers will be taken over by Bank
Nasional Indonesia (BNI), he added.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the Indonesian government
closed down 16 troubled private banks in a bid to improve the
efficiency of the banking system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
