<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tergat Sets World Best at Milan Half Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Paul Tergat celebrated his
fifth consecutive victory at the Milan Half Marathon by setting a
world best time in 59 minutes 17 seconds on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The world 10,000 meters champion shattered the previous record
of 59 minutes 43 seconds registered by Portugal's Antonio Pinto in
Lisbon on March 15.
</P>
<P>
Tergat's fellow countryman Philip Tarus finished second in one
hour and 24 seconds, followed by Morocco's Khalid Khannouchi in
1:01:21 at the third place.
</P>
<P>
"I was completely focused on the record, I wanted to break it,
I thought of nothing else," the 29-year-old Tergat said after the
race.
</P>
<P>
Tergat, who broke free from the leading pack with eight
kilometers remaining, said if he had not consumed too much energy
by starting off too fast, he would possibly complete the journey
within 59 minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
