<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increases Electromechanical Exports to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China's 1997 export volume of
electromechanical products to Africa hit 1.24 billion US dollars,
a three-fold rise on the figure for five years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Chinese exports of related products accounted for only
a small proportion of the African market, according to a recent
issue of the International Trade News. The issue also carried an
article reporting that 100-odd Chinese exporters attended a
recent forum on increasing electrochemical exports to Africa.
</P>
<P>
The publication noted that improvements are required for the
quality, reliability, technological content and after-sale
services for exported products, and concerned enterprises must
exhibit greater flexibility in face of the competitive African
market.
</P>
<P>
An official with the National Chamber of Commerce stressed that
exploring the African market does not necessarily center solely on
selling products. He stressed that China should increase the
availability of electromechanical products and should at the same
explore the global market by combining African resources with
Chinese technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
