<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls King "One of the Greatest Heroes" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
marking the 30th anniversary of Martin Luther King Jr.'s
assassination Saturday, called him "one of America's greatest
heroes."
</P>
<P>
The late civil rights leader was shot and killed as he left his
motel room in Memphis, Tennessee, in 1968.
</P>
<P>
"Let me just pause a moment to observe the 30th anniversary of
the death of one of America's greatest heroes, Dr. Martin Luther
King," Clinton said in his weekly radio address to the nation.
</P>
<P>
"His dream, deeply rooted in the American dream, is a dream for
all Americans," said Clinton, who just completed a 12-day trip to
Africa. "It's a dream, as I recently saw, shared by millions and
millions of people around the world."
</P>
<P>
"Let us here at home always strive to heed Dr. King's words and
live up to his legacy," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
