<DOCNO> XIE19980405.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> March Honors Martin Luther King Jr.'s Memory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of marchers walked
the streets of Memphis, Tennessee, of the United States Saturday
on the 30th anniversary of the assassination of Martin Luther King
Jr.
</P>
<P>
The marchers followed a route much like the one the then
39-year-old civil rights leader led in his last march in Memphis a
week before he was gun down on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
Thirty years ago King was murdered when he came to help a
garbage workers strike.
</P>
<P>
"The bullet could not stop the dream. The bullet could not stop
a new generation from arising," news reports quoted the Rev. Jesse
Jackson as telling marchers before they departed from a church
near downtown Memphis where the garbage workers protest originated
in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Jackson was below the motel balcony on which King was standing
when he was killed by a single rifle shot.
</P>
<P>
Marchers filled the streets eight and more abreast stretching
at one point for about nine blocks.
</P>
<P>
The participants sang some of the anthems of the civil rights
rallies of the 1960s -- "We Shall Overcome" and "Ain't Gonna Let
Nobody Turn Me Around," according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Among those with Jackson in the front of the march were
Washington, D.C. Mayor Marion Barry, the Rev. Fred Shuttlesworth,
a pioneer of the civil rights movement, and musician-actor Isaas
Hayes.
</P>
<P>
The three-day commemoration of King's death began with a
memorial service Friday night and includes seminars and other
events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
